#  jax.numpy.reshape  # 

jax.numpy.  reshape  (  _ a  _ , _ shape  =  None  _ , _ order  =  'C'  _ , _ *  _ , _ newshape  =  Deprecated  _ , _ copy  =  None  _ )  [ [source]  ](https://github.com/jax-ml/jax/blob/main/jax/_src/numpy/lax_numpy.py#L2069-L2162) # 
    

Return a reshaped copy of an array. 

JAX implementation of [ ` numpy.reshape()  ` ](https://numpy.org/doc/stable/reference/generated/numpy.reshape.html#numpy.reshape "\(in NumPy v2.2\)") , implemented in terms of [ ` jax.lax.reshape()  ` ](jax.lax.reshape.html#jax.lax.reshape "jax.lax.reshape") . 

Parameters  : 
    

  * <::marker>

**a** ( _ArrayLike_ ) – input array to reshape 

  * <::marker>

**shape** ( _DimSize_ _|_ _Shape_ _|_ _None_ _|_ _None_ ) – integer or sequence of integers giving the new shape, which must match the size of the input array. If any single dimension is given size ` -1  ` , it will be replaced with a value such that the output has the correct size. 

  * <::marker>

**order** ( [ _str_ ](https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#str "\(in Python v3.13\)") ) – ` 'F'  ` or ` 'C'  ` , specifies whether the reshape should apply column-major (fortran-style, ` "F"  ` ) or row-major (C-style, ` "C"  ` ) order; default is ` "C"  ` . JAX does not support ` order="A"  ` . 

  * <::marker>

**copy** ( [ _bool_ ](https://docs.python.org/3/library/functions.html#bool "\(in Python v3.13\)") _|_ _None_ _|_ _None_ ) – unused by JAX; JAX always returns a copy, though under JIT the compiler may optimize such copies away. 

  * <::marker>

**newshape** ( _DimSize_ _|_ _Shape_ _|_ _DeprecatedArg_ ) – deprecated alias of the ` shape  ` argument. Will result in a [ ` DeprecationWarning  ` ](https://docs.python.org/3/library/exceptions.html#DeprecationWarning "\(in Python v3.13\)") if used. 



Returns  : 
    

reshaped copy of input array with the specified shape. 

Return type  : 
    

[ Array ](jax.Array.html#jax.Array "jax.Array")

Notes 

Unlike [ ` numpy.reshape()  ` ](https://numpy.org/doc/stable/reference/generated/numpy.reshape.html#numpy.reshape "\(in NumPy v2.2\)") ,  ` jax.numpy.reshape()  ` will return a copy rather than a view of the input array. However, under JIT, the compiler will optimize-away such copies when possible, so this doesn’t have performance impacts in practice. 

<::after>

<::before><::after>See also 

  * <::marker>

[ ` jax.Array.reshape()  ` ](jax.Array.reshape.html#jax.Array.reshape "jax.Array.reshape") : equivalent functionality via an array method. 

  * <::marker>

[ ` jax.numpy.ravel()  ` ](jax.numpy.ravel.html#jax.numpy.ravel "jax.numpy.ravel") : flatten an array into a 1D shape. 

  * <::marker>

[ ` jax.numpy.squeeze()  ` ](jax.numpy.squeeze.html#jax.numpy.squeeze "jax.numpy.squeeze") : remove one or more length-1 axes from an array’s shape. 




Examples 
    
    
    >>> x = jnp.array([[1, 2, 3],
    ...                [4, 5, 6]])
    >>> jnp.reshape(x, 6)
    Array([1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6], dtype=int32)
    >>> jnp.reshape(x, (3, 2))
    Array([[1, 2],
           [3, 4],
           [5, 6]], dtype=int32)
    

<::after> Copy to clipboard 

You can use ` -1  ` to automatically compute a shape that is consistent with the input size: 
    
    
    >>> jnp.reshape(x, -1)  # -1 is inferred to be 6
    Array([1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6], dtype=int32)
    >>> jnp.reshape(x, (-1, 2))  # -1 is inferred to be 3
    Array([[1, 2],
           [3, 4],
           [5, 6]], dtype=int32)
    

<::after> Copy to clipboard 

The default ordering of axes in the reshape is C-style row-major ordering. To use Fortran-style column-major ordering, specify ` order='F'  ` : 
    
    
    >>> jnp.reshape(x, 6, order='F')
    Array([1, 4, 2, 5, 3, 6], dtype=int32)
    >>> jnp.reshape(x, (3, 2), order='F')
    Array([[1, 5],
           [4, 3],
           [2, 6]], dtype=int32)
    

<::after> Copy to clipboard 

For convenience, this functionality is also available via the [ ` jax.Array.reshape()  ` ](jax.Array.reshape.html#jax.Array.reshape "jax.Array.reshape") method: 
    
    
    >>> x.reshape(3, 2)
    Array([[1, 2],
           [3, 4],
           [5, 6]], dtype=int32)

#  jax.numpy.mean  # 

jax.numpy.  mean  (  _ a  _ , _ axis  =  None  _ , _ dtype  =  None  _ , _ out  =  None  _ , _ keepdims  =  False  _ , _ *  _ , _ where  =  None  _ )  [ [source]  ](https://github.com/jax-ml/jax/blob/main/jax/_src/numpy/reductions.py#L803-L863) # 
    

Return the mean of array elements along a given axis. 

JAX implementation of [ ` numpy.mean()  ` ](https://numpy.org/doc/stable/reference/generated/numpy.mean.html#numpy.mean "\(in NumPy v2.2\)") . 

Parameters  : 
    

  * <::marker>

**a** ( _ArrayLike_ ) – input array. 

  * <::marker>

**axis** ( _Axis_ _|_ _None_ ) – optional, int or sequence of ints, default=None. Axis along which the mean to be computed. If None, mean is computed along all the axes. 

  * <::marker>

**dtype** ( _DTypeLike_ _|_ _None_ _|_ _None_ ) – The type of the output array. Default=None. 

  * <::marker>

**keepdims** ( [ _bool_ ](https://docs.python.org/3/library/functions.html#bool "\(in Python v3.13\)") ) – bool, default=False. If true, reduced axes are left in the result with size 1. 

  * <::marker>

**where** ( _ArrayLike_ _|_ _None_ _|_ _None_ ) – optional, boolean array, default=None. The elements to be used in the mean. Array should be broadcast compatible to the input. 

  * <::marker>

**out** ( _None_ _|_ _None_ ) – Unused by JAX. 



Returns  : 
    

An array of the mean along the given axis. 

Return type  : 
    

[ Array ](jax.Array.html#jax.Array "jax.Array")

<::after>

  * <::marker>

[ ` jax.numpy.average()  ` ](jax.numpy.average.html#jax.numpy.average "jax.numpy.average") : Compute the weighted average of array elements 

  * <::marker>

[ ` jax.numpy.sum()  ` ](jax.numpy.sum.html#jax.numpy.sum "jax.numpy.sum") : Compute the sum of array elements. 




Examples 

By default, the mean is computed along all the axes. 
    
    
    >>> x = jnp.array([[1, 3, 4, 2],
    ...                [5, 2, 6, 3],
    ...                [8, 1, 2, 9]])
    >>> jnp.mean(x)
    Array(3.8333335, dtype=float32)
    

<::after> Copy to clipboard 

If ` axis=1  ` , the mean is computed along axis 1. 
    
    
    >>> jnp.mean(x, axis=1)
    Array([2.5, 4. , 5. ], dtype=float32)
    

<::after> Copy to clipboard 

If ` keepdims=True  ` , ` ndim  ` of the output is equal to that of the input. 
    
    
    >>> jnp.mean(x, axis=1, keepdims=True)
    Array([[2.5],
           [4. ],
           [5. ]], dtype=float32)
    

<::after> Copy to clipboard 

To use only specific elements of ` x  ` to compute the mean, you can use ` where  ` . 
    
    
    >>> where = jnp.array([[1, 0, 1, 0],
    ...                    [0, 1, 0, 1],
    ...                    [1, 1, 0, 1]], dtype=bool)
    >>> jnp.mean(x, axis=1, keepdims=True, where=where)
    Array([[2.5],
           [2.5],
           [6. ]], dtype=float32)
